  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - RANGER</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>RANGERS, BLACKBURROW, AND TRAINING TIPS</font> - <small>Navarra of 7th Hammer, Seventh Hammer</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>First, some notes about training that will make your life easier as a higher-level ranger if you have the sense to do them as a newbie.

1. Make SURE you have thrown at LEAST 1 point of training into Taunt, Sense Heading, Archery, and Forage, and Track. Use them CONSTANTLY as you run around QHills. Also put at least a point into Bandage Wound. Let me explain each one:

- Use as you kill things - TAUNT everything! For some reason I didn't put any training points into taunt until lvl 17 or 18, but on the day I did, I went from skill lvl 4 to 100 in it with about 4 hours of play in HHK. Your role as ranger on the lower lvls will often be to get mobs off the easily killed classes (casters) or to act as a puller. Use this skill, love it; it can help save your party's lives.

- FORAGE is important because you can use it to find food/water for CRs or when you are a far run from the nearest vendor, for finding fishing grubs, for finding foodstuffs to use in baking or even things like smithing (materials for dyes). 

- SENSE HEADING is useful for anyone, especially if you get it up high enough that you won't need a compass any longer. (buying a compass is about 2pp+ and is a wonderful thing to buy, but Sense Heading is free, and you can use it when on CR's, very important!)

- TRACK is soooo important as a ranger! First, your track list will tell you what mobs are close to you and what their levels are in relation to you. As you get better and better at Track, you will eventually be able to track people and mobs all the way across a full zone, even a huge zone like WK. The only unfortunate thing about Track is it tracks in 2D, which can be aggrevating when you get to multi-level zones like dungeons, castles or even in BB. Still extremely useful skill, and you can even use it to make money for yourself later in your career.

- ARCHERY is one of the best skills to have as a Ranger. Most players don't use bow & arrows, thus underusing one of the best methods of pulling! And, so, when playing in a zone like Blackburrow (or later, SK) where many spawns drop arrows, they are more than willing to let you loot arrows or to outright give them to you. 

- BANDAGE WOUND can be used for you to heal yourself or others without using mana. Believe me, rangers can be real mana sinks for casters if you get heavily damaged and they have to heal you up. Bandages are relatively cheap, and if you get yourself a sewing kit, you can make your own bandages for free, plus make it through several levels of tailoring! 
   [Recipe for bandages: put two spiderling silks into sewing kit, hit combine, you will get silk threads. Take threads out, repeat with a second pair of spiderling silks. Now put two silk threads into the kit - do not stack them - and combine to create a silk bandage. These two recipes never fail and should take you up to about 10 skill in tailoring.]

Blackburrow has some great benefits as a ranger. You can learn to track, get lots of arrows as loot, practice your archery tons, and learn how to effectively use your new-found spells after level 9. I would not actually recommend going there until you are about level 7 or 8, preferrably 9, and try to get yourself a full suit of banded before you go. (Banded costs 1pp per AC - ie boots should cost you 6pp. If you find a nice player, especially one practicing their smithing, you may get a discount if you're purchasing more than 1 piece at a time.) 

AC is *the* lifesaver of rangers, and at levels 6-14, banded will be a good friend indeed to you. However there is some nice drops in BB, and the Elites drop two highly prized items for low-level chars: studded and spiked collars. These are common drops but of the two, the spiked is the better to get. 

BB is notorious for trains and with good reason - the spawns are close and in easy aggro range of one another, the fighting areas are tight, and if your target gets away from you and starts wandering, he's 95% likely to bring back a friend or five on the way. The best place to be out of trains' way is on the Elite ledge (straight through med room from ramp to top), but the spawns here run 11-15, so be careful fighting here. You too can end up pulling a nasty train from this area, so it is best advised to take on the Ledge only with a group. 

The worst spots for trains are the Med Room (the room at the bottom of the ramp leading down from the grassy level) or on the ramp itself. Fighting on the ramp is difficult because the spawns keep running up and down, and it is just tunnel carpal just waiting to happen. The Snake Pit is usually not too bad unless some higher lvl chars pull a train out of the Commander's room - then watch out!

The best strategy for being a ranger (9+) in BB is to act as puller for your group. Run in towards your prey a little way, pick your target carefully, smack them with an arrow, run back to your group's safe melee spot. At this point the casters should hit with the first DD/DOT, you should hit with Flame Lick (DOT) and the main tank should move in to start smacking the mob. You should also throw on your Snare spell when the mob is at/near/below 50%, and then jump in to start dishing out the damage. 

Remember, newbie rangers: you are NOT a tank! At the lower levels, yes, you can do a fair amount of tanking, but you are not designed to be a tank forever. (It has taken me 20 lvls to learn this but hey, at least I learned. Take my advice early!) 

You should at this level be working hard on your Taunt, Track, Archery skills. Use your mana to Snare and DOT, and do your minor buffs. Admit you're a mana sink for casters at this point - your Minor Heal is ok but you have to recast it so many times it's practically useless. Use that bandage wound skill! And use it to bandage yourself up to 50% before either self-healing or requesting heal, unless of course you're practically walking death. :-) 

Learning to play a ranger well is a tough job at times, but you will probably feel more of a sense of accomplishment than many other classes. Do not be discouraged that your exp usually levels slower than others, because remember, you have cool tricks (ie Track) that no other class has. Good luck to you and may Karana guide your footsteps!


Navarra Meritage of Amazon Storm
Ranger of 20 seasons
Seventh Hammer server

</td></tr>
